        "content": "<p>i thought the ← arrow pointing nowhere   (←<br>\n(e.g. in <code>let val ← x (← mvarId.getType) (← mvarId.getTag)</code>)</p>\n<p>is quite a confusing syntax. </p>\n<p>I understand it is to 'bind a monad', but am confused the exact meaning. (kind of like the result of a function call, <code>(← y)</code> is like <code>y()</code> in e.g. python?)</p>\n<p>also, is <code>let x ← y</code> sometimes a syntactic sugar for <code>let x ← (← y)</code>, or does it always have a consistent meaning?</p>",
        "id": 528511614,
        "sender_full_name": "Ping J",
        "timestamp": 1752392625
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"937033\">Ping J</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/dangling.20.E2.86.90.20arrows/near/528511614\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>also, is <code>let x ← y</code> sometimes a syntactic sugar for <code>let x ← (← y)</code>, or does it always have a consistent meaning?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It's almost always the same as <code>let x := (← y)</code></p>",
        "id": 528512431,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1752393548
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but it is also legal for it to mean let x := y, right?</p>",
        "id": 528512621,
        "sender_full_name": "Ping J",
        "timestamp": 1752393783
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you're comparing to Python, Lean's <code>let val ← x (← mvarId.getType) (← mvarId.getTag)</code> is Python's<code>val = await x (await mvarId.getType) (await mvarId.getTag)</code></p>",
        "id": 528512632,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1752393795
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh i see, thx~</p>",
